Subject: [PATCH 5/5] wasm: expose mCore audio buffer to JS via getAudioSamples
Author: pi-extension-gba vendor-builder

ADR 0006 (docs/decisions/0006-mcore-audio-rebuild.md) Option A: add a
minimal pull-based audio bridge so Phase 8b (audio subprocess) can read
s16le stereo PCM out of the SDL-free WASM host without relinking SDL.

Design, after investigating the post-0004 source tree
(/src/include/mgba/core/core.h, /src/src/gba/core.c,
/src/src/util/audio-buffer.c inside the vendor Docker image):

  * mGBA's mCore already exposes a fully resampled, interleaved stereo
    `mAudioBuffer*` via `core->getAudioBuffer(core)`. It is populated
    incrementally from inside `core->runFrame(core)`. The upstream SDL
    path pulled from it via `mSDLRunAudio`; we pull from it via a new
    JS-callable KEEPALIVE. No blip_buf, no new C files, no new link
    edges.

  * Default GBA sample rate is 16.78 MHz / 0x8000 = 32_768 Hz (see
    /src/src/gba/audio.c:46) — matches docs/design/phase-8-audio-plan.md
    L7 exactly, so no setIntegerCoreSetting("audioSampleRate") hook
    needs re-adding (ADR 0006 §Risks).

  * The buffer is two-channel (GBA audio.c delegates to GBAudioInit
    which calls mAudioBufferInit(&audio->buffer, AUDIO_BUFFER_SAMPLES,
    2) — /src/src/gb/audio.c:54), with circle-buffer capacity
    0x4000 = 16384 frames. `core->setAudioBufferSize(core, 2048)` sets
    the *producer threshold*, not the capacity, so 2048 plays nicely
    with a 16384-frame ring without risk of overflow-drop between JS
    reads at ~60 Hz.

  * `mCoreSyncProduceAudio` / `mCoreSyncLockAudio` / `mCoreSyncConsumeAudio`
    all NULL-guard (see /src/src/core/sync.c:82,98,114). Our SDL-free
    host never calls `core->setSync`, so `audio->p->sync` is NULL and
    the in-core production path simply writes samples to the ring
    buffer without throttling. This is exactly what we want for a
    pull-based consumer.

  * `mAudioBufferRead(buf, dest, count)` treats `count` as *frames*
    (stereo pairs), reading `count * 2 * sizeof(int16_t)` bytes
    interleaved L,R,L,R... and returning the actual frame count read.
    Maps 1:1 to the ADR 0006 signature
    `getAudioSamples(int16_t* dest, uint32_t maxFrames) -> actualFrames`.

This patch makes three additive edits to the post-0004 main.c:

  1. Add `#include <mgba-util/audio-buffer.h>` for mAudioBufferRead.
  2. In `loadGame`, after `core->setVideoBuffer(...)` and before
     `core->reset(...)`, call `core->setAudioBufferSize(core, 2048)` to
     match docs/design/phase-8-audio-plan.md L7 (2048-frame producer
     threshold).
  3. Add `EMSCRIPTEN_KEEPALIVE uint32_t getAudioSamples(int16_t* dest,
     uint32_t maxFrames)` between the pixel-buffer accessors and the
     runFrame export. Returns the actual number of stereo *frames*
     written into `dest` (not raw int16_t samples), never blocks,
     writes zero frames if the core is uninitialised or the ring is
     empty. The JS caller must allocate `dest` at >= maxFrames * 2 *
     sizeof(int16_t) bytes (e.g. Int16Array(4096) for maxFrames=2048).

No CMakeLists.txt changes: the mCore library is already linked into
mgba.js and `mAudioBufferRead` lives in the same archive
(libmgba.a -> /src/src/util/audio-buffer.c, confirmed at
/src/build-wasm/CMakeFiles/mgba.dir/src/util/audio-buffer.c.o). Symbol
export is achieved by `EMSCRIPTEN_KEEPALIVE` alone, matching the
pattern used for runFrame / getPixelBuffer / buttonPress / ... added
by patches 0002 and 0004.

Apply with: patch -p1 < 0005-mcore-audio.patch
Base commit: thenick775/mgba @ be30a34e913da1ba7f040d3db4e10f700ce49f76
Depends on: 0001, 0002, 0003, 0004 (patches to the already-stripped
main.c).

--- a/src/platform/wasm/main.c
+++ b/src/platform/wasm/main.c
@@ -34,6 +34,7 @@
 #include <mgba/core/serialize.h>
 #include <mgba/core/interface.h>
 #include <mgba/core/version.h>
+#include <mgba-util/audio-buffer.h>

 #include <emscripten.h>

@@ -119,6 +120,34 @@
 	return GBA_FB_H;
 }

+/* ----- Audio buffer accessor (ADR 0006, vendor patch 0005) ----- */
+
+/*
+ * getAudioSamples: pull-style reader for mCore's internal stereo ring
+ * buffer. Returns the number of STEREO FRAMES (not samples) written
+ * into `dest`; each frame is two int16_t values, interleaved L,R.
+ *
+ * Semantics:
+ *   - Non-blocking. If fewer frames are available than `maxFrames`,
+ *     writes fewer and returns the actual count.
+ *   - Returns 0 if the core is uninitialised (no ROM loaded), if the
+ *     core has no audio buffer yet (shouldn't happen post-loadGame),
+ *     or if `dest` is NULL / `maxFrames` is zero.
+ *   - Caller MUST size `dest` at >= maxFrames * 2 * sizeof(int16_t)
+ *     bytes (e.g. Int16Array(4096) for maxFrames=2048).
+ *
+ * The underlying circle buffer is populated incrementally from within
+ * `core->runFrame(core)`. Drain every tick to avoid dropped samples;
+ * the 16 384-frame ring gives ~0.5 s of slack at 32 768 Hz.
+ */
+EMSCRIPTEN_KEEPALIVE uint32_t getAudioSamples(int16_t* dest, uint32_t maxFrames) {
+	if (!core || !dest || maxFrames == 0) return 0;
+	struct mAudioBuffer* buf = core->getAudioBuffer(core);
+	if (!buf) return 0;
+	size_t got = mAudioBufferRead(buf, dest, (size_t) maxFrames);
+	return (uint32_t) got;
+}
+
 /* ----- Frame stepping ----- */

 /* Advance the emulator by one video frame. JS calls this from the render
@@ -390,6 +419,13 @@
 	mCoreAutoloadPatch(core);

 	core->setVideoBuffer(core, videoBuffer, GBA_FB_W);
+
+	/* Set audio producer threshold to 2048 frames, matching
+	 * docs/design/phase-8-audio-plan.md L7. Ring-buffer capacity is
+	 * fixed at AUDIO_BUFFER_SAMPLES = 0x4000 = 16 384 frames inside
+	 * mCore; this call only adjusts the batching threshold. */
+	core->setAudioBufferSize(core, 2048);
+
 	core->reset(core);

 	keyMask = 0;
